messages.content:
Hey! I'm having a really frustrating performance issue with my React app. Basically, every time I type in a search input, the entire page re-renders and it's super laggy. I've been trying to figure this out for hours and I'm just stuck. Here's my main component:

```tsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import { ProductCard } from './ProductCard';
import { SearchBar } from './SearchBar';
import { FilterPanel } from './FilterPanel';
import { CartSummary } from './CartSummary';

// ProductList component
// Created: March 2026
// Author: dev team
// Last modified: April 2026
// Description: Main product listing page with search and filters
// TODO: Add pagination
// TODO: Add sorting
// FIXME: Performance issues with search

interface Product {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  price: number;
  category: string;
  rating: number;
  image: string;
  description: string;
}

interface CartItem {
  product: Product;
  quantity: number;
}

export function ProductList() {
  const [products, setProducts] = useState<Product[]>([]);
  const [searchQuery, setSearchQuery] = useState('');
  const [selectedCategory, setSelectedCategory] = useState('all');
  const [cart, setCart] = useState<CartItem[]>([]);
  const [isLoading, setIsLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);

  // Fetch products from API
  useEffect(() => {
    // Set loading state
    setIsLoading(true);
    // Clear any previous errors
    setError(null);
    // Make the API call
    fetch('/api/products')
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => {
        // Set the products
        setProducts(data);
        // Set loading to false
        setIsLoading(false);
      })
      .catch(err => {
        // Set the error message
        setError(err.message);
        // Set loading to false
        setIsLoading(false);
      });
  }, []);

  // Filter products based on search and category
  const filteredProducts = products.filter(product => {
    const matchesSearch = product.name.toLowerCase().includes(searchQuery.toLowerCase()) ||
      product.description.toLowerCase().includes(searchQuery.toLowerCase());
    const matchesCategory = selectedCategory === 'all' || product.category === selectedCategory;
    return matchesSearch && matchesCategory;
  });

  // Calculate cart total
  const cartTotal = cart.reduce((total, item) => total + (item.product.price * item.quantity), 0);

  // Get unique categories
  const categories = [...new Set(products.map(p => p.category))];

  // Handle adding item to cart
  const addToCart = (product: Product) => {
    setCart(prevCart => {
      const existingItem = prevCart.find(item => item.product.id === product.id);
      if (existingItem) {
        return prevCart.map(item =>
          item.product.id === product.id
            ? { ...item, quantity: item.quantity + 1 }
            : item
        );
      }
      return [...prevCart, { product, quantity: 1 }];
    });
  };

  if (isLoading) return <div>Loading...</div>;
  if (error) return <div>Error: {error}</div>;

  return (
    <div className="product-page">
      <SearchBar value={searchQuery} onChange={setSearchQuery} />
      <div className="content">
        <FilterPanel
          categories={categories}
          selected={selectedCategory}
          onSelect={setSelectedCategory}
        />
        <div className="product-grid">
          {filteredProducts.map(product => (
            <ProductCard
              key={product.id}
              product={product}
              onAddToCart={() => addToCart(product)}
            />
          ))}
        </div>
        <CartSummary items={cart} total={cartTotal} />
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

I ran the React profiler and here's the output:

```
Profiler [ProductList] (5 renders)
  Render 1: 2.4ms (mount)
  Render 2: 145.2ms (state update: searchQuery "a")
    → ProductCard ×47 re-rendered (145.1ms total)
    → FilterPanel re-rendered (0.8ms)
    → CartSummary re-rendered (1.2ms)
    → SearchBar re-rendered (0.3ms)
  Render 3: 142.8ms (state update: searchQuery "ap")
    → ProductCard ×47 re-rendered (142.5ms total)
    → FilterPanel re-rendered (0.7ms)
    → CartSummary re-rendered (1.1ms)
  Render 4: 139.4ms (state update: searchQuery "app")
    → ProductCard ×47 re-rendered (139.1ms total)
    → FilterPanel re-rendered (0.8ms)
    → CartSummary re-rendered (1.0ms)
  Render 5: 141.0ms (state update: searchQuery "appl")
    → ProductCard ×47 re-rendered (140.7ms total)
    → FilterPanel re-rendered (0.7ms)
    → CartSummary re-rendered (1.2ms)
```

So basically every single ProductCard is re-rendering every time I type a character, even the ones that don't match the search. Can you help me figure out what's going on and how to fix it?

Arrow functions in JSX are fine for simple cases, but here's the issue: if you wrap `ProductCard` in `React.memo()`, it will skip re-rendering when its props haven't changed. But if `addToCart` is recreated every render, it's a *new* function reference each time — so `React.memo` thinks the props changed even though the function does the same thing.

Think of it like mailing the same letter but in a different envelope each time. The content is identical but the recipient sees a "new" delivery.

`useCallback` keeps the same function reference between renders, so `React.memo` can properly skip re-renders.

Here's the fix:

```tsx
// Memoize expensive computations
const filteredProducts = useMemo(() =>
  products.filter(product => {
    const matchesSearch = product.name.toLowerCase().includes(searchQuery.toLowerCase()) ||
      product.description.toLowerCase().includes(searchQuery.toLowerCase());
    const matchesCategory = selectedCategory === 'all' || product.category === selectedCategory;
    return matchesSearch && matchesCategory;
  }), [products, searchQuery, selectedCategory]
);

const cartTotal = useMemo(() =>
  cart.reduce((total, item) => total + (item.product.price * item.quantity), 0),
  [cart]
);

const categories = useMemo(() =>
  [...new Set(products.map(p => p.category))],
  [products]
);

// Stable function reference
const addToCart = useCallback((product: Product) => {
  setCart(prevCart => {
    const existingItem = prevCart.find(item => item.product.id === product.id);
    if (existingItem) {
      return prevCart.map(item =>
        item.product.id === product.id
          ? { ...item, quantity: item.quantity + 1 }
          : item
      );
    }
    return [...prevCart, { product, quantity: 1 }];
  });
}, []);
```

Then wrap `ProductCard` in `React.memo`. The combination of stable refs + memo = skip re-renders.

Good catch. The issue is subtle — `filteredProducts` returns a *new array* from `.filter()` every time, even if the same products are in it. And in your JSX you're creating a new arrow function for each card:

```tsx
onAddToCart={() => addToCart(product)}
```

That `() => addToCart(product)` creates a new function on every render for every card, bypassing `React.memo`.

Two fixes:

1. Pass the product ID and let the card call `addToCart` with it:
```tsx
<ProductCard
  key={product.id}
  product={product}
  onAddToCart={addToCart}
/>
```

Then in ProductCard:
```tsx
const ProductCard = React.memo(({ product, onAddToCart }) => {
  return <button onClick={() => onAddToCart(product)}>Add</button>
});
```

2. For the filtered array, the cards that don't match are already removed from the DOM — they *aren't* rendering. The 47 that re-render are the ones that *do* match. The profiler is telling you all matching cards re-render because `filteredProducts` is a new array reference.

If you have many matching products and individual cards are expensive, consider virtualization with `react-window` — only render what's visible in the viewport.
